"Shanks G.D., Hay S.I., Stern D.I., Biomndo K., Snow R.W.","Meteorologic influences on Plasmodium falciparum malaria in the highland tea estates of Kericho, western Kenya",2002,"Emerging Infectious Diseases","8","12",,"1404","1408",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0036913275&partnerID=40&md5=130e296141ce9063e2468f7b09902cc6","U.S. Army Med. Research Unit-Kenya, Nairobi, Kenya; University of Oxford, Oxford, United Kingdom; Kenya Medical Research Institute, Wellcome Trust Collab. Programme, Nairobi, Kenya; Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, Troy, NY, United States; Brooke Bond Central Hospital, Kericho, Kenya; Armed Forces Inst. of the Med. Sci., APO AP 96546, United States; TALA Research Group, Department of Zoology, University of Oxford, South Parks Road, Oxford OX1 3PS, United Kingdom","Shanks, G.D., U.S. Army Med. Research Unit-Kenya, Nairobi, Kenya, Armed Forces Inst. of the Med. Sci., APO AP 96546, United States; Hay, S.I., University of Oxford, Oxford, United Kingdom, Kenya Medical Research Institute, Wellcome Trust Collab. Programme, Nairobi, Kenya, TALA Research Group, Department of Zoology, University of Oxford, South Parks Road, Oxford OX1 3PS, United Kingdom; Stern, D.I., Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, Troy, NY, United States; Biomndo, K., Brooke Bond Central Hospital, Kericho, Kenya; Snow, R.W., University of Oxford, Oxford, United Kingdom, Kenya Medical Research Institute, Wellcome Trust Collab. Programme, Nairobi, Kenya","Recent epidemics of Plasmodium falciparum malaria have been observed in high-altitude areas of East Africa. Increased malaria incidence in these areas of unstable malaria transmission has been attributed to a variety of changes including global warming. To determine whether the reemergence of malaria in western Kenya could be attributed to changes in meteorologic conditions, we tested for trends in a continuous 30-year monthly malaria incidence dataset (1966-1995) obtained from complete hospital registers at a Kenyan tea plantation. Contemporary monthly meteorologic data (1966-1995) that originated from the tea estate meteorologic station and from global climatology records were also tested for trends. We found that total hospital admissions (malaria and nonmalaria) remained unchanged while malaria admissions increased significantly during the period. We also found that all meteorologic variables showed no trends for significance, even when combined into a monthly suitability index for malaria transmission. We conclude that climate changes have not caused the highland malaria resurgence in western Kenya.",,"altitude; article; climate; disease transmission; epidemic; greenhouse effect; hospital admission; human; incidence; Kenya; malaria; meteorology; nonhuman; Plasmodium falciparum; Altitude; Climate; Disease Outbreaks; Humans; Incidence; Kenya; Malaria, Falciparum; Registries",,,,,,"Garnham, P.C.C., Malaria epidemics at exceptionally high altitudes in Kenya (1945) BMJ, 11, pp. 45-47; Strangeways-Dixon, D., Paludrine (proguanil) as a malarial prophylactic amongst African labour in Kenya (1950) East Afr Med J, 27, pp. 127-130; Malakooti, M.A., Biomndo, K., Shanks, G.D., Reemergence of epidemic malaria in the highlands of western Kenya (1998) Emerg Infect Dis, 4, pp. 671-676; Garnham, P.C.C., The incidence of malaria at high altitudes (1948) Journal of the National Malaria Society, 7, pp. 275-284; Lindblade, K.A., Walker, E.D., Onapa, A.W., Katungu, J., Wilson, M.L., Land use change alters malaria transmission parameters by modifying temperature in a highland area of Uganda (2000) Trop Med Int Health, 5, pp. 263-274; Van der Stuyft, P., Manirankunda, L., Delacollette, C., L'approche de risque dans le diagnostic du paludisme-maladie en regions d'altitude (1993) Annales de la Société Belge de Médecine Tropicale, 73, pp. 81-89; Bashford, G., Richens, J., Travel to the coast by highlanders and its implications for malaria control (1992) Papua New Guinea Medical Journal, 35, pp. 